To find the value of $\dbinom{n}{1}$ for any positive integer $n$, we consider the number of ways to choose 1 object from $n$ objects. This is arguably the simplest possible option for making a choice. Therefore, $\dbinom{n}{1}=n$. In this example, $\dbinom{5}{1}=5$. We could have also worked this out in the following way: \begin{align*} \dbinom{n}{1} &=\frac{n!}{k!(n-k)!}\\ &=\frac{n}{1!(n-1)!}\\ &=\frac{n}{1\cdot (n-1)!}\\ &=\frac{n}{(n-1)!} \cdot \frac{1}{1}\\ &= n \end{align*}
You are differentiating the formula, but you got an incorrect result. The correct differentiation gives \begin{align*} \frac{d}{dn}\dbinom{n}{1} &=n \end{align*}
with which the answer to your question is $\bf{n}$.

